SIMPLE: insulate
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Insulate
<hw>In"su*late</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Insulated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Insulating</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>insulatus</ets> insulated, fr. <ets>insula</ets> island. See
<er>Isle</er>, and cf. <er>Isolate</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To make an island of.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Pennant.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To place in a detached situation, or in a state
having no communication with surrounding objects; to isolate; to
separate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Elec. & Thermotics)</fld> <def>To prevent the
transfer of electricity or heat to or from (bodies) by the interposition
of nonconductors.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Insulating stool</b></col> <fld>(Elec.)</fld>, <cd>a
stool with legs of glass or some other nonconductor of electricity, used
for insulating a person or any object placed upon it.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 773 --></p>

<p><ent>Insulated</ent>⟦br⟧
